In article <2ltofv$dtn@news.umbc.edu>, olson@umbc.edu (Bryan G. Olson; CMSC (G)) writes:
> There seems to be an ongoing myth that the Tuchman scheme with either
> two or three keys has some deep security property.  The only reason
> for the scheme is to allow hardware implementations to be compatible
> with one key DES by loading the same key in all three iterations.
> There is no evidence that encrypt-decrypt-encrypt is any more secure
> than encrypt-encrypt-encrypt.

That's now true.  Until comparatively recently, it was feared that
DES might be a group -- that encryption with two different keys might
be equivalent to since encryption with some third key.  It has since been
proved that DES is not a group.
